Stereotype.name: Application Component
Stereotype.notes: An application component is defined as a modular, deployable, and replaceable part of a software system that encapsulates its behavior and data and exposes these through a set of interfaces.
Stereotype.baseStereotypes: Financial%20Funding Standards%20Classification Review Lifecycle Interested%20Parties Metrics Security Version Provisioning Data%20Layer Privacy Support Function%20of%20Application Information%20Management Vendors Configuration Business%20Continuity%20and%20Disaster%20Recovery Technical%20Condition%20Scores Business%20Value%20Scores Risk%20Value%20Scores Application%20Layer Presentation%20Layer

Tag.description: Distinguishing between applications and components

Stereotype.name: Application Interface
Stereotype.notes: An application interface is defined as a point of access where an application service is made available to a user or another application component.

Tag.name: Interface Type
Tag.values: User Interface,Shared File,Shared Database,Web Service,API,Queue,Database Read Only,Database Read-Write

Stereotype.name: Application Database
Stereotype.notes: A specialised application component that stores data and is defined as a passive element suitable for automated processing.

Stereotype.name: Application Service
Stereotype.notes: An application service is defined as a service that exposes automated behavior.

Tag.name: Rating
Tag.description: Fit for purpose rating 0 - doesn't exist to 5 excellent

Stereotype.name: Data Object
Stereotype.notes: A data object is defined as a passive element suitable for automated processing.

Tag.name: Type
Tag.description: Use to indicate specialisation of data object and change shape from standard archimate notation to message or database.

Stereotype.name: Application Collaboration
Stereotype.notes: An application collaboration is defined as an aggregate of two or more application components that work together to perform collective behavior.

Stereotype.name: Application Function
Stereotype.notes: An application function is defined as a behavior element that groups automated behavior that can be performed by an application component.

Stereotype.name: Application Interaction
Stereotype.notes: An application interaction is defined as a behavior element that describes the behavior of an application collaboration.

Stereotype.name: ETL
Stereotype.notes: Specialised database interface for Extract Transform and Load

Stereotype.name: DBRO
Stereotype.notes: Specialised database interface for Read Only

Tag.name: Primary Better Public Services
Tag.description:
The Better Public Services result area most linked to the application's function.
1. Reduce the number of people who have been on a working age benefit for more than 12 months. 2. Increase participation in early childhood education. 3. Increase infant immunisation rates and reduce the incidence of rheumatic fever. 4. Reduce the number of assaults on children. 5. Increase the proportion of 18-year-olds with NCEA level 2 or equivalent qualification. 6. Increase the proportion of 25 to 34-year-olds with advanced trade qualifications, diplomas and degrees. 7. Reduce the rates of total crime, violent crime and youth crime. 8. Reduce reoffending. 9. New Zealand businesses have a one-stop online shop for all government advice and support they need to run and grow their business. 10. New Zealanders can complete their transactions with the Government easily in a digital environment. N/A No linked result area.

Tag.description: Risk that information is compromised (e.g., altered, stolen, or deleted) due to an internal or external attack. 5 is the highest risk.
